    {/* ============ Section 4: Four problems ============ */}
    <div class="fc-section-head">
      <div class="eyebrow-row">
        <span class="fc-eyebrow">The 12-month thesis</span>
      </div>
      <h2>From 170,000 to 1,000,000 households.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="fc-framing">
      <p class="quote">Many things that work at 170,000 households break at 1 million.</p>
      <p class="tail">These are the four that matter most in the next 12 months.</p>
    </div>

    {/* --------- Problem 1 --------- */}
    <article class="fc-problem">
      <div class="pr-num">01</div>
      <h3 class="pr-title">Personalisation - the app treats 170,000 households the same way</h3>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Problem</span>
        <p>
          The <em class="c">"Today"</em> home page is editorially curated but identical for every user. <em class="c">"Your usuals"</em> is a passive reorder list - it shows what you have bought before but does nothing predictive with that data. There is no neighbourhood intelligence, no individual feed. FirstClub sits on one of the richest behavioural datasets in Indian consumer commerce and uses <strong>almost none of it</strong> at the product surface.
        </p>
        <div class="fc-callout">A browse experience that shows everyone the same content becomes repetitive by order 10. Personalisation is what keeps the browse model fresh at scale.</div>
        <p>
          And unlike any competitor, FirstClub has a <strong class="k">structural data advantage</strong>: a concentrated user base in identifiable apartment societies. That is <em class="c">community data</em>, not just location data.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Solution</span>
        <span class="pr-sub">Personalised Home Page</span>
        <p>
          Move from one editorial <em class="c">"Today"</em> feed to a dynamically composed page per user. A household that primarily orders fresh produce sees different featured sections than one that orders supplements and imported snacks. Category weights, featured brands, and occasion collections respond to individual order history and browse behaviour. <strong>The UX structure stays the same - the content layer becomes personal.</strong>
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">ML-Powered "Your Usuals"</span>
        <p>
          Transform the tab from a static list to a <strong>predictive replenishment engine</strong>. The system learns individual consumption cadences per category. If a user buys curd every 5-7 days, surface it on day 5 with a contextual nudge. When a product is out of stock, suggest a quality-matched substitute that has passed the same ingredient standards - not just the nearest price match. The goal is to eliminate the gap between <em class="c">"I need this"</em> and <em class="c">"it arrives"</em> without the user having to think about it.
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">Society-Level Recommendations</span>
        <p>
          A feature showing <em class="c">"Most ordered in your society this week"</em> or <em class="c">"Your neighbours are trying this"</em> does three things simultaneously: provides social proof without relying on public internet reviews, drives discovery of unfamiliar brands through trusted community behaviour, and reinforces the club identity. An unfamiliar brand ordered by <strong>40 families in your building</strong> does not feel unfamiliar anymore. <strong>No competitor can build this</strong> without replicating FirstClub's concentrated go-to-market.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Success Metrics</span>
        <p>
          Orders per month: personalised feed users vs. control group. Add-to-cart rate on ML-surfaced <em class="c">"Your usuals"</em> nudges vs. manual reorder. Click-through and conversion on society recommendations. Repeat purchase rate on products first discovered through society data.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">ROI</span>
        <p>
          A 1-2 additional SKU per basket from a well-timed nudge or society recommendation is <strong class="k">₹150-300 per order</strong>. At <strong>4+ orders per month</strong> across <strong>170,000 households</strong>, even a conservative <strong class="k">15% basket lift</strong> from personalisation represents significant GMV. The compounding value is <em class="c">stickiness</em> - a product that learns you is structurally harder to replace than one that lists things.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    {/* --------- Problem 2 --------- */}
    <article class="fc-problem">
      <div class="pr-num">02</div>
      <h3 class="pr-title">Multi-city quality at scale is an unsolved product problem</h3>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Problem</span>
        <p>
          Quality curation in Bengaluru is <em class="c">founder-led and manual</em> - blind taste tests, personal supplier relationships, central ingredient checks. This is the right approach for 0 to 1. <strong>Hyderabad has just launched</strong> with 3 stores. Hyderabad's food culture is materially different: biryani masala, mutton, Irani chai, local dairy. A Bengaluru-mirrored catalogue will underperform. But there is no product infrastructure to run a Hyderabad-specific curation in parallel - no tool for local supplier discovery, no system for city-specific testing, no way to manage two city catalogues without doubling manual effort.
        </p>
        <div class="fc-callout">Founder-led curation is the right tool for proof of concept. It is the wrong tool for five cities simultaneously.</div>
        <p>
          Series B capital is explicitly allocated to <strong>geographic expansion</strong>. If each new city requires the same leadership involvement as Bengaluru, expansion becomes the bottleneck. If quality is inconsistent across cities, the trust built over two years in Bengaluru gets damaged nationally <em class="c">before it exists</em>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Solution</span>
        <span class="pr-sub">Curation OS - Internal Tool</span>
        <p>
          A lightweight internal product for the category team to manage supplier onboarding, blind test scoring, ingredient compliance tracking, and catalogue approval per city. This process currently lives in spreadsheets and WhatsApp. Systematising it allows a team of <strong>3-4 people</strong> to run curation across multiple cities <em class="c">simultaneously</em> rather than sequentially. The product that makes quality scalable without headcount growing linearly with geography.
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">Community Sourcing for Local Curation</span>
        <p>
          A <em class="c">"nominate a brand"</em> mechanism for FirstClub members in each new city. They know the local premium landscape better than a Bengaluru-based category team. A nominated brand should receive a quality test invite within <strong>2 weeks</strong> - speed of response is the difference between a city feeling locally owned and one that feels centrally managed. Converts engaged local users into <em class="c">brand evangelists</em>.
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">Local Occasion Calendar</span>
        <p>
          Each city runs its own festival cycle. Hyderabad: <em class="c">Eid, Bathukamma</em>. Chennai: <em class="c">Pongal</em>. Mumbai: <em class="c">Ganesh Chaturthi</em>. Auto-surface city-specific occasion collections based on the local calendar rather than defaulting to Bengaluru's. Lightweight infrastructure change, high local relevance signal.
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">Dark Store Micro-Assortment Intelligence</span>
        <p>
          A store near a tech park serves a different household profile than one near a multigenerational residential colony. Build a rule system for store-level assortment customisation within the city catalogue - core SKUs stay fixed across all stores, a portion flexes based on neighbourhood data. <strong>Quality stays consistent; assortment stays locally relevant.</strong>
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">Quality Consistency Audits</span>
        <p>
          Supplier quality at onboarding is not the same as supplier quality at month 18. Build quarterly spot-check re-testing for high-volume SKUs already in the catalogue. The quality promise should not <em class="c">degrade silently</em> as supplier relationships age and volume pressure builds.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Success Metrics</span>
        <p>
          Time from city launch to first 10,000 orders - Hyderabad baseline vs. next city. Repeat purchase rate at 30 days in new city vs. Bengaluru benchmark. % of city catalogue locally sourced by day 90. SKUs managed per category manager across cities.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">ROI</span>
        <p>
          A city that launches with a localised catalogue retains <strong class="k">20-30% more users</strong> in the first 90 days than one that feels imported. At <strong>₹1,200 AOV</strong> and 4+ orders per month, <strong>5,000 additional retained households</strong> in a single city represents <strong class="k">₹2.9 crore in additional annualised GMV</strong>. Across 4 city launches, the infrastructure investment pays back in the first city. Every city after that is <em class="c">compounding return</em>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    {/* --------- Problem 3 --------- */}
    <article class="fc-problem">
      <div class="pr-num">03</div>
      <h3 class="pr-title">Discovery gap - customers do not trust what they cannot recognise</h3>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Problem</span>
        <p>
          <strong>60% of the catalogue</strong> is exclusive or unfamiliar brands. Product copy is good but brand context does not exist - no explanation of why a brand passed the quality bar, what was tested, what the panel found. A real user described opening the app as <em class="c">"the same feeling as walking into a Nature's Basket - a subtle fear of overspending"</em> - triggered before a single price is seen. The quality promise is the entire brand, but it is <strong>invisible at the point of purchase</strong>.
        </p>
        <div class="fc-callout">In Bengaluru, word-of-mouth in premium apartment clusters does the trust-building work. That does not travel.</div>
        <p>
          Every new city launch starts from zero brand recognition. The product has to earn trust without human referrals - and today it cannot.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Solution</span>
        <span class="pr-sub">"Why This Brand" Chip on Every Product Card</span>
        <p>
          One line, specific, factual - not marketing copy. <em class="c">"Cold-pressed in small batches. No hexane extraction."</em> Requires a structured data layer behind every SKU. <strong>Highest-leverage, lowest-effort change</strong> in this set.
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">Brand Story Micro-Pages Inside the App</span>
        <p>
          3-4 screens per brand, accessible from the product card with a single tap. Founder photo, origin, what the curation team found, one quote from the tasting panel. Contextual and in the purchase flow - not a separate section the user has to navigate to.
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">Pre-Delivery Expectation Setting</span>
        <p>
          The green bag, coriander in dry leaves, and founder note are physical surprises today. Surface them digitally immediately after the first order is placed - a lightweight screen showing <em class="c">"Here is what arrives with your order."</em> Converts first-order anxiety into anticipation. Retains the delight without losing it to uncertainty.
        </p>
        <span class="pr-sub">"People Who Buy X Also Trust Y"</span>
        <p>
          When a user views an unfamiliar brand, surface a connection to a brand they already order. Bridge the unfamiliar through the familiar using existing order data. <strong>No new content required.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Success Metrics</span>
        <p>
          Add-to-cart rate on exclusive SKUs vs. known brands. Time from app open to first add-to-cart for new city users. Repeat purchase rate on brands first tried through discovery features. Basket size: users who engage with brand story vs. those who do not.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">ROI</span>
        <p>
          A <strong class="k">10% improvement in add-to-cart rate</strong> on the 60% of catalogue that is exclusive has a direct AOV impact at every order across every household. The strategic number is <em class="c">wallet share</em> - every rupee spent on Blinkit because a brand felt unfamiliar is a rupee FirstClub did not earn. The discovery gap is the mechanism by which that leakage happens. Fixing it compounds across <strong>170,000 households</strong> and every new city cohort.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    {/* --------- Problem 4 --------- */}
    <article class="fc-problem">
      <div class="pr-num">04</div>
      <h3 class="pr-title">The membership product does not exist</h3>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Problem</span>
        <p>
          Ayyappan has publicly stated FirstClub's end-state is <em class="c">Costco-style</em> - profit from membership fees, products at near-cost. Today there is no paid membership. <em class="c">"Subscribe"</em> is auto-delivery scheduling. Every rupee of revenue is transactional GMV. <strong>The platform is a premium delivery app, not yet a club.</strong>
        </p>
        <div class="fc-callout">The 170,000 households placing 4+ orders per month are the warmest membership audience FirstClub will ever have.</div>
        <p>
          Every month without a membership ask, they form habits as free users, making conversion harder later. More importantly, the Costco model cannot be validated unless it is built. <strong>A working membership product at small scale is worth more in a Series C conversation than a plan to launch one.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Solution</span>
        <p>
          Launch a <strong>Founding Member programme</strong> - <strong class="k">5,000 limited slots</strong>, early-adopter pricing - within the next 3 months. This is not a commercial launch. It is a <em class="c">learning vehicle</em>: iterate on benefit architecture, pricing, and conversion mechanics before the stakes are high. Benefits should feel like <em class="c">access, not discounts</em> - exclusive SKUs, tasting panel invites, clubhouse access, early brand drops. Priced at <strong class="k">₹1,199/year</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Full commercial membership launch is the right call at approximately <strong>400,000-500,000 total households</strong>. At that scale, 25% conversion = <strong class="k">100,000+ paying members × ₹1,200/year = ₹12-15 crore ARR</strong> at near-zero marginal cost. That is when membership becomes a P&L line, not just a signal. <strong>The architecture built at 5,000 members scales directly to 100,000.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">Success Metrics</span>
        <p>
          Founding Member conversion rate. Orders per month: paid member vs. free user. AOV: member vs. non-member. Membership retention at 3, 6, and 12 months.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">ROI</span>
        <p>
          Revenue at current scale is not the point. <strong>The Founding Member programme proves the Costco model works in India.</strong> At 400K+ households it becomes a core revenue stream. The architecture built today at 5,000 members scales to 100,000 without rebuilding.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

